				<h3 class="header-admission">English language requirements</h3><br>
				<div class="text-admission">
					<p>
						Our languages department supports students coming from abroad and being new to English. Support is provided for
						students joining KG1 to Grade 9,
						who require assistance in English. To learn more about our English as Additional Language (EAL) Programme for
						Grade 6 to Grade 9, click here.
					</p>

					<p>English language requirements for our bilingual and language acquisition streams increase as students approach
						the IB Diploma grades.
						Please note that the below are minimal requirements for entry into grades 6 to 9.</p>

					<ul>
						<li>PreKG to G5 – students may enter as non-English speakers until mid-year in grade 5.</li>
						<li>G6 – A.2.1 Junior</li>
						<li>G7 – A.2.2 Junior</li>
						<li>G8 – B.1 Junior</li>
						<li>G9 – B.2 Junior</li>
						<li>Grades 10 to 12 – Students must be able to function independently in English.</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<!-- second section -->
				<h3 class="header-admission">French and German requirements for Bilingual Streams </h3>
				<div class="text-admission">
					<p>The following language proficiency levels are minimal indicative requirements
						at the start of the school year for admission to the respective bilingual grades:</p>

					<ul>
						<li>PreKG and KG1 – no specific language requirements</li>
						<li>KG2 aiming at G1 E+ – basic understanding and oral command of French or German, exposure to French or German
							at home</li>
						<li>KG2 aiming at G1 bilingual – oral Portfolino A.1 level, exposure to F or G at home</li>
						<li>G1 –A.1.1 Primary</li>
						<li>G2 – A.1.2 Primary</li>
						<li>G3 – A.2.1 Primary</li>
						<li>G4 – A.2.2 Primary</li>
						<li>G5 – B.1.1 Primary</li>
						<li>G6 – A.2.1 Junior</li>
						<li>G7 – A.2.2 Junior</li>
						<li>G8 – B.1 Junior</li>
						<li>G9 – B.2 Junior</li>
						<li>Grades 10 to 12 – students must be able to follow a native curriculum in either French or German</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
